{"id":"1707.07840","submitter":"Ioannis Kleftogiannis","authors":"Ioannis Kleftogiannis, Ilias Amanatidis","title":"Entanglement and edge effects in superpositions of many-body Fock states\n  with spatial constraints","comments":"8 pages, 3 figures, published in EPJ B","journal-ref":"Eur. Phys. J. B (2020) 93: 84","doi":"10.1140/epjb/e2020-100625-y","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate how entangled states can be created by considering collections\nof point-particles arranged at different spatial configurations, i.e., Fock\nstates with spatial constraints. This type of states can be realized in Hubbard\nchains of spinless hard-core bosons, at different fillings, which have gapped\nenergy spectrum with a highly degenerate ground state. We calculate the\nbipartite entanglement entropy for superpositions of such Fock states and show\nthat their entanglement can be controlled via the spatial freedom of the\nparticles, determined by the system filling. In addition we study the effect of\nconfinement/boundary conditions on the Fock states and show that edge modes\nappear at the ends of the system, when open boundary conditions are considered.\nOur result is an example of entangled many-body states in 1D systems of\nstrongly interacting particles, without requiring the spin, long-range\nmicroscopic interactions or external fields. Instead, the entanglement can be\ntuned by the empty space in the system, which determines the spatial freedom of\nthe interacting particles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Jul 2017 07:47:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 22 Dec 2017 11:24:14 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 12 Apr 2019 11:31:53 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 26 May 2020 10:25:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-05-27"}
